Let’s do this practical exercise step-by-step. We will create a tiny Node.js application, 
build it using an optimized multi-stage Dockerfile, tag it locally with both a specific version tag (v1.0.0) and the latest tag, 
and push it up to Docker Hub.Before we start, replace YOUR_DOCKERHUB_USERNAME in the commands below with your actual Docker Hub username.

🛠️ Step-by-step Practical Guide1.

Create your project files:
Create a new directory on your computer, open a terminal inside it, 
and create these two simple files:app.js (Our tiny app)

JavaScriptconst http = require('http');
const server = http.createServer((req, res) => {
    res.writeHead(200, { 'Content-Type': 'text/plain' });
    res.end('Hello! This app is successfully running inside a tiny multi-stage container!\n');
});
server.listen(3000, () => console.log('Server running on port 3000'));

package.json (App metadata)JSON{
  "name": "tiny-node-app",
  "version": "1.0.0",
  "main": "app.js",
  "scripts": {
    "start": "node app.js"
  }
}

2.Write the Multi-Stage Dockerfile:2 mins.Create a file named Dockerfile (no file extension) in the same directory. 
We will use the exact concept we discussed: compiling/preparing dependencies in a heavy node environment, 
and transferring only the running code to a lightweight Alpine image.

Dockerfile
# Stage 1: The Builder (heavy environment)
FROM node:20 AS builder
WORKDIR /build
COPY package*.json ./
RUN npm install
COPY . .

# Stage 2: The Runtime (ultra-lightweight Alpine environment)
FROM node:20-alpine AS runner
WORKDIR /app
# Copy only the prepared application files from the builder stage
COPY --from=builder /build .
EXPOSE 3000
CMD ["npm", "start"]

3.Log into Docker Hub via CLI:1 min.Open your terminal and authenticate your local computer with Docker Hub. 
Enter your Docker Hub username and password when prompted:Bashdocker login

4.Build and Tag the Images:2 mins.We need to build the Dockerfile. 
In standard industry practice, we tag the image twice: 
once with the exact version release number and once with latest so users can always pull the newest default build easily.
Run these two commands in your terminal (make sure to include the trailing dot .):

Bash# 
1. Build and tag with a specific version number
docker build -t YOUR_DOCKERHUB_USERNAME/tiny-node-app:v1.0.0 .

# 2. Tag that exact same build image as 'latest'
docker tag YOUR_DOCKERHUB_USERNAME/tiny-node-app:v1.0.0 YOUR_DOCKERHUB_USERNAME/tiny-node-app:latest

5.Push both tags to Docker Hub:2 mins.Now push both matching image tags up to your cloud repository on Docker Hub:

Bash
# Push the versioned copy
docker push YOUR_DOCKERHUB_USERNAME/tiny-node-app:v1.0.0

# Push the latest copy
docker push YOUR_DOCKERHUB_USERNAME/tiny-node-app:latest

🔎 Verifying Your Work
Once the push steps finish, log into your browser dashboard at hub.docker.com. 
Navigate to your repository page, click on the Tags tab, and you will see your freshly uploaded images populated clearly.
